kuhu@stud.uni-sb.de (Kurt Huwig) once said:

> Kurt Huwig (kuhu@stud.uni-sb.de) wrote:
> : David Sternlight (strnlght@netcom.com) wrote:                [FUD alert!]
> : : False. RSA is patentable in Europe but cannot be patented because of prior
> : : publication. IDEA was patented in Europe.

> Does this mean that PGP is illegal to use in Europe due to the IDEA patent?
> As I know PGP exchanges a session key with RSA and encrypts with IDEA.

It is not. Ascom AG (the patent holder of IDEA) has given permission to
use IDEA in PGP for both non-commercial and commercial uses, as is
explained in the PGP DOCS. Any version of PGP that is written outside
the US is completely legal to use in europe. This includes versions of
PGP upto 2.3a, and version 2.6ui.


